### Arrays in C#

An array stores a fixed-size sequential collection of elements of the same type.

### Declaring Arrays

```csharp
int[] numbers;                // Declaration
int[] numbers = new int[5];   // Declaration with size
int[] numbers = new int[] { 1, 2, 3 };  // Declaration with values
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3 };  // Shorthand
```

### Array Indexing

Arrays are zero-indexed. The first element is at index 0.

```csharp
int[] arr = { 10, 20, 30, 40, 50 };
Console.WriteLine(arr[0]);   // 10
Console.WriteLine(arr[2]);   // 30
arr[4] = 55;                 // Change last element
```

### Array Properties

| Property | Description | Example |
|----------|-------------|---------|
| `Length` | Total number of elements | `arr.Length` |
| `Rank` | Number of dimensions | `arr.Rank` |
| `IsFixedSize` | Always true for arrays | `arr.IsFixedSize` |
| `IsReadOnly` | Is the array read-only | `arr.IsReadOnly` |

### Iterating Over Arrays

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 2, 4, 6, 8 };

// For loop with index
for (int i = 0; i < numbers.Length; i++)
{
    Console.WriteLine(numbers[i]);
}

// Foreach
foreach (int num in numbers)
{
    Console.WriteLine(num);
}
```

### Array Initialization

```csharp
// All elements default to 0
int[] arr1 = new int[5];  // { 0, 0, 0, 0, 0 }

// Explicit initialization
int[] arr2 = new int[3] { 1, 2, 3 };
int[] arr3 = { 1, 2, 3 };

// Using Enumerable
int[] arr4 = Enumerable.Range(0, 10).ToArray();  // { 0, 1, ..., 9 }
```

> **Key Point:** Arrays have a fixed size determined at creation. Use `Length` property (not `Count()` method) to get array size. Arrays are reference types, so assigning one array to another creates a reference, not a copy.

### Reference Behavior

```csharp
int[] original = { 1, 2, 3 };
int[] copy = original;  // Both reference the same array
copy[0] = 99;
Console.WriteLine(original[0]);  // 99
```

codeExample:
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        int[] scores = { 85, 92, 78, 95, 88 };

        Console.WriteLine($"Array length: {scores.Length}");
        Console.WriteLine("\nAll scores:");

        int sum = 0;
        foreach (int score in scores)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"- {score}");
            sum += score;
        }

        double average = (double)sum / scores.Length;
        Console.WriteLine($"\nAverage: {average:F2}");
    }
}
